[2] Fighting Ebola now
Date: 21 Jan 2015
Source: Crown Agents [edited]
http://www.crownagents.com/news-and-know-how/ebola-blog/ebola-blog/2015/01/20/who-where-and-how-providing-the-people-to-help-fight-ebola


Since working on the Ebola response, a number of practicalities and truths have become very clear about who is needed in Sierra Leone for all the roles involved in the Ebola fight, who we [Crown Agents] are able to get, and how we can get them out there.

Because of the fast moving nature of Ebola and the necessary speed of the response, we've needed people who are experienced enough in the relevant fields for them to hit the ground running. We've also needed to get them out there quickly, with minimal visa delays and transport difficulties (see more below). ... - more

Passengers going to and from Ebola affected countries are now not allowed to transit through Nairobi and Johannesburg. As these are 2 of Africa's most important transport hubs, it's very difficult to get people from other African countries to Sierra Leone. Some of the routes have taken up to 72 hours to get people to Freetown. To get someone from Malawi to Sierra Leone recently, for example, we had to book a route that sent them from Malawi, through Addis Ababa in Ethiopia, up to Istanbul in Turkey, then across to Casablanca in Morocco before eventually connecting through to Freetown. ... - more

Visa issues can easily hold up a deployment. We've been working closely with our visa agent to make sure that everyone we need to send out there has the appropriate visa rights and has things like landing cards, which they need in order to get into Sierra Leone once the plane lands. We've also had to design routes around visa issues in the connecting airports. ... - more

Our experience in getting people to Sierra Leone has highlighted the difficulties and restrictions there are in trying to make use of the global workforce to fight Ebola. ... -more

[Byline: Wilfred Gortor]

